Heat a drizzle of @oil{a drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} on high heat. Once hot, add the @chicken thigh{260%g}(diced) and cook, stirring regularly, until browned and cooked through, ~{8-10%minutes}. 

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

Transfer the chicken to a #plate{} but keep the pan.

Meanwhile, fill and boil your #kettle{}.

Peel and grate the @garlic clove{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Trim the @spring onion{1} then slice thinly.

Halve the @red chilli{1/2} lengthways, deseed then finely chop.

Zest the @lime{1/2} and cut into wedges.

Halve the @broccoli florets{200%g}.

Halve the @yellow pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Slice into thin strips.

Put the now empty frying pan back on high heat and, when hot, add the broccoli
and pepper and stir-fry until golden, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Meanwhile, bring a #saucepan{} of water up to the boil with the water from your kettle and @salt{0.25%tsp} for the noodles.

When boiling, add the @egg noodle nest{2} and cook until tender, ~{4%minutes}. Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and drizzle with oil to prevent them sticking together.

Add the garlic and the chilli (use less chilli if you don't like heat) to the pan with the broccoli. Stir-fry for ~{1%minute} then add a splash of water to help the vegetables cook through.

Meanwhile, whisk the @ketjap manis{25%g}, @soy sauce{25%g} and @peanut butter{1} in a #jug{} with @water{50%ml} until well combined.

Return the chicken to the pan and add the noodles and peanut sauce mixture.

Mix together and cook until everything is piping hot, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Divide the stir fry between #plates{}, sprinkle over the lime zest, spring onion and any remaining chilli.

Serve with the lime wedges for squeezing over. Enjoy!